{"parse":{"title":"Sign name","pageid":3106159,"revid":823994922,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Deaf_culture\" title=\"Deaf culture\">Deaf culture</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Sign_language\" title=\"Sign language\">sign language</a>, a <b>sign name</b> (or a <b>name sign</b>) is a special sign that is used to uniquely identify a person, just like a name. In the American Deaf community, there are some special cultural rules around sign names; for example, they must be agreed upon by the named person and the broader <a href=\"/wiki/Deaf_culture\" title=\"Deaf culture\">Deaf community</a>. This ensures that no one else in the community already has the same sign name or that the same sign has a different meaning. Until a person receives a sign name, the person's name is usually <a href=\"/wiki/Fingerspelling\" title=\"Fingerspelling\">fingerspelled</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#In_different_cultures\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">In different cultures</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Further_reading\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Further reading</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"In_different_cultures\">In different cultures</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sign_name&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: In different cultures\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">See also: <a href=\"/wiki/ASL_name_sign\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"ASL name sign\">ASL name sign</a></div>\n<p>Different deaf cultures appear to have different customs around sign names. For example, in the <a href=\"/wiki/Deaf_American\" title=\"Deaf American\">Deaf American</a> community, sign names are usually subdivided into two naming systems: descriptive (DNS) and arbitrary (ANS).<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The DNS system manually illustrates physical features, and the ANS system is the first letter of their English name applied to one or more locations. An ANS sign is usually just a unique sign without other meaning, but there may be family patterns, like all the children in a family having names signed at the chin.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Swedish_Sign_Language\" title=\"Swedish Sign Language\">Swedish Sign Language</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/French_Sign_Language\" title=\"French Sign Language\">French Sign Language</a>, it is the DNS system that dominates. In <a href=\"/wiki/British_Sign_Language\" title=\"British Sign Language\">British Sign Language</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Japanese_Sign_Language\" title=\"Japanese Sign Language\">Japanese Sign Language</a>, people may be named with a lexical sign for something related to them. In Japanese Sign Language, sign names for males tend to be articulated with the thumb prominent, and those for females gave the pinky tending to be prominent, corresponding to the general use of those digits in signs denoting males and females respectively.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (March 2015)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup><sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (July 2015)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>\n</p><p>The practice has a counterpart in North <a href=\"/wiki/American_Indian_and_Alaska_Native\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"American Indian and Alaska Native\">American Indian</a> practices in which (spoken) names were also acquired by a personality trait, a physical feature, or especially a defining memorable event, and in which a name might also change if a still more significant occasion seemed to call for it.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sign_name&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Swinbourne, Charlie (18 June 2008). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/ouch/features/sign_names.shtml\">\"What's your Sign Name?\"</a>. <i>BBC \u2013 Ouch! (disability) \u2013 Features</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">26 September</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=BBC+%E2%80%93+Ouch%21+%28disability%29+%E2%80%93+Features&amp;rft.atitle=What%27s+your+Sign+Name%3F&amp;rft.date=2008-06-18&amp;rft.aulast=Swinbourne&amp;rft.aufirst=Charlie&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.bbc.co.uk%2Fouch%2Ffeatures%2Fsign_names.shtml&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASign+name\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:0-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Supalla, Samuel James (1992). <i>The Book of Name Signs</i>. DawnSignPress. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0915035308\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0915035308\">0915035308</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Book+of+Name+Signs&amp;rft.pub=DawnSignPress&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft.isbn=0915035308&amp;rft.aulast=Supalla&amp;rft.aufirst=Samuel+James&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASign+name\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sign_name&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation book\">Erting, Carol (1994). <i>The Deaf Way</i>. Washington: Gallaudet University Press. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>